 :post/body-markdown
 "## What Kotoba is

Kotoba is a small **Clojure-shaped language profile** for compiling
capability-checked programs to WebAssembly. It's aimed at code that should
be inspectable, portable, and constrained: AI-generated cells, sandboxed
automation, repository policy, and other untrusted programs where the host
decides which capabilities are available.

Three things up front, since 'Clojure-shaped' invites the obvious pushback:

1. **It's a Clojure-family *profile/subset*, not a full Clojure or
   ClojureScript implementation.** Canonical source extension is `.kotoba`;
   `.clj`, `.cljc`, and `.cljs` are accepted as compatibility formats, with
   Kotoba-specific behavior selected via a `:kotoba` reader-conditional
   branch reachable only through `.cljc`'s wider branch chain (`.clj` and
   `.cljs` are single-target, mirroring each other). It is not \"any JVM
   Clojure or ClojureScript program runs.\"
2. **Compilation target is WebAssembly, compile-first.** The public surface
   is `kotoba -e` / `kotoba wasm ...` -- not an interpreter with a Wasm
   backend bolted on.
3. **Capability-confined safety is the point, not an add-on.** Capabilities
   are explicit, scoped, typed values (never ambient strings a module can
   summon by name); a host-side guard intersects what a module was actually
   handed against policy before any call runs.

## 30-second tour

```sh
kotoba -e '(+ 1 2)'
kotoba wasm build examples/hello.kotoba -o hello.wasm
kotoba wasm safe-policy examples/policy-demo.kotoba
kotoba wasm safe-build examples/policy-demo.kotoba --policy policy.edn -o policy-demo.wasm
```

## The implementation is itself Clojure

The compiler, CLI, and conformance tooling that process this Clojure-shaped
language are themselves written in Clojure/ClojureScript (`.cljc`) -- an
earlier Rust implementation was fully retired in favor of this CLJC
authority. Its capability-safety design is *benchmarked against* Rust's
ownership/borrow-safety model on an explicit safety ladder, not modeled on
or ported from it: Rust-style memory safety is treated as an insufficient
baseline that Kotoba's capability-confinement model (deny-by-default,
typed capabilities, signed audit receipts) is designed to exceed.

## Two narrow-slice decisions, both shipped honestly documented

Rather than a full Rust-style ownership/borrow/lifetime system, Kotoba
ships a narrow affine-typing layer scoped *only* to capability-typed
values: a capability handle may be consumed at most once per execution
path through a function (deterministic drop, no implicit clone). A full
ownership analysis was deliberately rejected -- on this project's own
safety ranking it would only reach \"Rust/Zig-grade\", strictly below the
capability-confinement target already shipped and byte-verified, and
memory safety was already achieved without one (free-less allocator +
bounds-checked accessors + no concurrency primitives). The narrow check has
a documented, known gap: tracking is per local binding name, not per
underlying value, so renaming a capability through a `let`-alias and using
both names once each is an uncaught double-use. That doesn't weaken the
actual runtime enforcement, which re-checks every use regardless of alias
-- but it's a real, named limitation, not swept under the rug.

Separately: `.cljs` was retired as a dedicated source extension in an
earlier profile version, on the argument that `.cljc` + `#?(:cljs ...)`
already covers what a standalone `.cljs` file would. That argument was
never wrong, exactly, but it also never accounted for porting friction --
people who already have `.cljs` code and don't want to rename files just
to try Kotoba. `.cljs` is back, but not as a return to full ClojureScript
compatibility: it's a single-target compatibility extension mirroring
`.clj`'s shape, not `.cljc`'s portable one.

## The rest of the stack

Alongside the language, [`kotoba-lang/kotobase`](https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotobase)
plays the role Datomic plays for Clojure -- same datom/EAVT/Datalog model,
but reimagined for the distributed web: content-addressed blake3/CIDv1
blocks instead of a single transactor over SQL/DynamoDB, a Prolly Tree
instead of a B-tree, an immutable commit DAG instead of a single log, and a
CACAO-authenticated edge runtime instead of a JVM peer with a direct
storage connection.

## Where to look

- Language contract: https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotoba-lang
- Compiler/runtime (CLJC, Rust-free): https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotoba
- Distributed-web Datomic: https://github.com/kotoba-lang/kotobase

## Question for this community

We just shipped two \"narrow slice, not the full thing\" calls back to
back (above): a capability-value-only affine check instead of a general
ownership system, and a single-target `.cljs` re-acceptance instead of
widening `.cljc`'s reach further. Both are documented as partial, with
their gaps named rather than hidden. Where's the line, in your experience,
between \"ship the narrow useful slice and document the gap\" and \"the
incomplete version creates more confusion than it resolves\"?"

